ProposalInformation.Title: OTE-16 Global Alignment-2
ProposalInformation.Abstract:
At this point the secondary has already been aligned (via GA-1 & Coarse MIMF). The SM position will only be adjusted for focus diversity in GA-2 and not for any additional corrections.
Our goal now is to correct radial decenter, clocking, and potentially radius of curvature of the PMSAs. Incidentally we correct tip and tilt to maintain the segment image array, although not to correct the PMSAs since they are still unstacked.
ProposalInformation.ObservingDescription:
Reduce the observed segment level WFE by refining the corrections for all PMSAs.
Like GA-1, this is a particularly complex part of commissioning.
At this point the secondary has already been aligned (via GA-1 & Coarse MIMF). The SM position will only be adjusted for focus diversity in GA-2 and not for any additional corrections.
Our goal now is to correct radial decenter, clocking, and potentially radius of curvature of the PMSAs. Incidentally we correct tip and tilt to maintain the segment image array, although not to correct the PMSAs since they are still unstacked.
There will be 20 observations for the selected target. Observations 1 takes initial GA focus diversity data for phase retrieval. Subsequent observations are on HOLD until WFSC scientist decides which ones to execute: • Observations 2-6 contain a set of visits for a radial translation correction. This process has to span across 5 observations as described below due the potential for disruption to the segment image array. Observations 7-11 and 12-16 are duplicates of that set, if needed for subsequent iterations. • Observation 17 contains a single visit for a “Correct+Adjust” type GA activity. This could be used for segment clocking or ROC corrections, or other moves that do not move segments in such a way as to disrupt the segment image array. Observations 18 and 19 are duplicates, if needed for subsequent iterations • Observation 20 is a single “Correct” type activity, to put the SM back to its nominal position.
See PIF for details.
